Thursday, February 14, 2013 |  Israel Today Staff.  
An Egyptian Christian leader living in the US is calling out the global Church, in particular the Catholic Church, for failing to champion the plight of Egypt's 8-10 million Coptic Christians, who are living increasingly dangerous conditions.
  Dr. Ashraf Ramelah, director of Voice of the Copts, wrote the following open letter to the Vatican to plead his case.
Dr. Ramelah's letter:
    Our mission is to raise awareness in the West about the plight of the Egyptian Christians and their struggle against Islamic supremacy. Born into a Coptic family in Cairo, Arabic was my native language while growing up. Today I find these assets valuable in interpreting and explaining current events as they pertain to the hidden realities of Islam and its impact on the free world.

Something I wrote in response to Kasa ;

~ ~ ~

St. Valentine's Day Massacre... name of the ppv where Stone Cold fought Vinny-Mac in a cage. Probably only Kasa knows what I'm talking about. :P

But yeah.... the only true, "real" relationship I've ever had lasted five years... and it was amazing. And V-Day finally had a meaning to me... but ever since the break-up, it just has served as a reminder of what I lost, along w/ our anniversary [April 17th] and her b-day [December 17th]. Love is magical and wonderful... until it ends, if it does. Which always changes things in a person's heart. :(

But it does get better. This year, today is the day I focus on me and making myself a better person. Christmas had been terrible the past two years because of it being the time of her b-day AND Christmas, one of our two fave holidays... but this past Christmas was wonderful for the first time in a while.

And Halloween was always our other favorite... we actually began a tradition where we would buy eachother small gifts on Halloween, because we almost liked it better than Christmas. I remember the year before the break-up, she bought me a collection of all of the Ninja Turtle movies... she knew me so well, and I loved it. I know I'll never forget her... and I'll always cherish the memories I have of her. But it does no good to dwell on the past.

All we can do is learn from yesterday, live for the moment, and move forward. Sorry about this being so long... but I tend to do that when I have something to write about. >_< Anywayz... hope today is a good day for you, Kasa, regardless of the holiday. Take care of yourself. :)
